  "prompt": "What is the modern periodic table in Hindi?",
  "response": "In Hindi, the modern periodic table is called \"\u0906\u0927\u0941\u0928\u093f\u0915 \u0906\u0935\u0930\u094d\u0924 \u0938\u093e\u0930\u0923\u0940\" (Aadhunik Aavart Saarni). Here are some key details:\n\n1. Hindi translation:\n- \"\u0906\u0927\u0941\u0928\u093f\u0915\" (Aadhunik) means Modern\n- \"\u0906\u0935\u0930\u094d\u0924\" (Aavart) means Periodic\n- \"\u0938\u093e\u0930\u0923\u0940\" (Saarni) means Table\n\n2. Key features of the periodic table are the same in Hindi as in English:\n- Elements are arranged by atomic number\n- Elements are organized in periods and groups\n- Elements are classified by their properties\n\n3. Element names in Hindi often have both Sanskrit-derived and English-derived versions.\n\nExample:\n- Hydrogen = \u0939\u093e\u0907\u0921\u094d\u0930\u094b\u091c\u0928 (Hydrogen) or \u091c\u0932-\u0924\u0924\u094d\u0935 (Jal-tatva)\n- Oxygen = \u0911\u0915\u094d\u0938\u0940\u091c\u0928 (Oxygen) or \u092a\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0923\u0935\u093e\u092f\u0941 (Pranavaayu)\n\nThe structure and scientific principles of the periodic table remain consistent across languages, including its Hindi representation.",
